   <abstract>Polygonum alpinum All (Polygonaceae) rhizomes was loaded in soxhlet for extraction with methanol and water as solvent. The extracts obtained were assayed for anti-inflammatory potency via carrageenan and formaldehyde prompted infection among experimental animals. The methanolic extract method presented potent anti-inflammatory activity in comparison to aqueous extract in both experimental models. Column chromatography was used for the isolation and characterization of active constituents in methanolic extract. Four active compounds, Octacosan-1-ol (1), Tridecane-1,9-diol (2), 4-hydroxybutyl acetate (3) and Octanoic acid (4) were isolated. Two dimensional NMR procedures were used for the characterization of isolated compounds. In-vitro anti-inflammatory potency of isolated compounds was assayed via Human RBC membrane stabilization and Protein denaturation methods. </abstract>
